    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@codex review\r\n\r\nre: **Keep deployment-value clients from overriding provider keys**\r\n\r\nI don't think this applies.\r\n\r\n`newChatTestOptions` does inject fake `ChatProviderAPIKeys`, but that only affects the chat daemon runtime path in `coderd.New`, so background chat execution stays on the local fake provider. The deployment-value tests that use `newChatClientWithDeploymentValues` are not asserting against that runtime provider map.\r\n\r\nThe code paths under test for those cases read deployment values directly via `ChatProviderAPIKeysFromDeploymentValues(api.DeploymentValues)` when computing provider availability / validation, for example in `getUserChatProviderAvailability`, `ListChatProviders`, and `hasEffectiveCentralProviderAPIKey`. They do not consult `options.ChatProviderAPIKeys` or `api.chatDaemon`'s injected provider keys.\r\n\r\nAlso, `ChatProviderAPIKeysFromDeploymentValues` is intentionally a no-op today and `TestChatProviderAPIKeysFromDeploymentValues/DoesNotReuseBridgeConfig` locks that down. So there is no deployment-derived chat key behavior here for the fake override to mask.\r\n\r\nIn other words, the injected fake provider is only there to keep actual chat execution local in tests that create chats. The deployment-value cases are still exercising the same deployment-policy path as before.",
